00:13:52,298 --> 00:13:54,533
Be responsible, have roots,

272
00:13:54,533 --> 00:13:55,668
get a job.

273
00:13:57,102 --> 00:13:57,937
- Where?

274
00:13:57,937 --> 00:13:59,071
Doing what?

275
00:13:59,071 --> 00:13:59,872
- I don't know.

276
00:14:01,307 --> 00:14:02,841
Maybe you could find me
  something at the factory.

277
00:14:02,841 --> 00:14:04,410
- The factory?

278
00:14:04,410 --> 00:14:05,778
You've been putting
 me down for years

279
00:14:05,778 --> 00:14:06,712
for working there.

280
00:14:06,712 --> 00:14:08,714
Too dull for you, remember?

281
00:14:08,714 --> 00:14:11,517
Too tedious for an exciting,

282
00:14:11,517 --> 00:14:14,186
imaginative person
  such as yourself.

283
00:14:15,554 --> 00:14:16,655
- I have to get
 some money so I can

284
00:14:16,655 --> 00:14:17,623
buy you out Nat.

285
00:14:19,725 --> 00:14:21,460
- You can not be serious.

286
00:14:21,460 --> 00:14:22,728
- I am real serious.

287
00:14:22,728 --> 00:14:24,496
- How do you expect to
get that kind of money?

288
00:14:24,496 --> 00:14:26,498
- I don't know, I'm gonna
  figure something out.

289
00:14:26,498 --> 00:14:27,600
I'm gonna do
 whatever it takes to

290
00:14:27,600 --> 00:14:29,468
keep this farm in the family.

291
00:14:29,468 --> 00:14:30,869
- Frannie, be reasonable.

292
00:14:30,869 --> 00:14:32,905
- I cannot believe
  that you let Jake

293
00:14:32,905 --> 00:14:35,507
talk you into such
 a hair-brained idea!

294
00:14:35,507 --> 00:14:36,575
- He didn't!

295
00:14:37,743 --> 00:14:39,912
We both want this.

296
00:14:39,912 --> 00:14:41,680
- Well then you
 both can forget it.

297
00:14:45,651 --> 00:14:48,554
(slow paced music)

298
00:14:55,628 --> 00:14:58,797
(loud horn whistling)

299
00:15:00,266 --> 00:15:02,968
- You're gonna be late.

300
00:15:02,968 --> 00:15:04,236
- Okay.

301
00:15:04,236 --> 00:15:06,972
Gee, what did they
  do to the windows?

302
00:15:14,880 --> 00:15:17,983
Hey, how come you got windows
 and the factory didn't?

303
00:15:17,983 --> 00:15:19,385
I bet people spent too much time

304
00:15:19,385 --> 00:15:21,887
looking out the window
 dreaming they had a life huh?

305
00:15:23,022 --> 00:15:24,923
It's probably more
 efficient windowless.

306
00:15:26,492 --> 00:15:29,695
- So you want to become
a part of our family.

307
00:15:29,695 --> 00:15:31,163
- Yes sir I do.

308
00:15:31,163 --> 00:15:32,998
- Your sister's a
 wonderful employee.

309
00:15:33,899 --> 00:15:35,467
If I recall, she went to college

310
00:15:35,467 --> 00:15:37,036
and you didn't, is that right?

311
00:15:37,036 --> 00:15:38,437
- [Frannie] Yes sir.

312
00:15:38,437 --> 00:15:40,172
She went to Piedmont community
 college for two years.

313
00:15:40,172 --> 00:15:42,708
She had to stop when
our mom first got sick.

314
00:15:42,708 --> 00:15:44,610
If you want the absolute truth,

315
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:45,978
I didn't like school.

316
00:15:45,978 --> 00:15:47,579
I wasn't school material.

317
00:15:51,784 --> 00:15:53,419
- You don't have
 experience in the type

318
00:15:53,419 --> 00:15:54,920
of production we do here.

319
00:15:54,920 --> 00:15:56,355
- No but I learn fast.

320
00:15:56,355 --> 00:15:58,557
When I learned to ride a
 bike, I got it the first time.

321
00:15:58,557 --> 00:16:00,092
Same with water-skis.

322
00:16:00,092 --> 00:16:01,327
Well actually,
 that took me a day,

323
00:16:01,327 --> 00:16:02,961
but most people
  don't ever get up.

324
00:16:02,961 --> 00:16:04,463
Definitely not the first day.

325
00:16:06,165 --> 00:16:07,566
- Do you know what we do here?

326
00:16:07,566 --> 00:16:09,034
- Sort of.

327
00:16:09,034 --> 00:16:10,402
- We package.

328
00:16:10,402 --> 00:16:13,138
Sew and fold certain products.

329
00:16:14,840 --> 00:16:16,575
- Men's underwear.

330
00:16:16,575 --> 00:16:17,910
Cotton and silk.

331
00:16:21,380 --> 00:16:23,182
- Tell me about
 your job experience.

332
00:16:24,817 --> 00:16:27,720
- Photocopy centers,
 two restaurants,

333
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:28,721
and an old age home.

334
00:16:28,721 --> 00:16:30,756
I only lasted two days.

335
00:16:30,756 --> 00:16:32,791
The smell got to me.

336
00:16:32,791 --> 00:16:34,493
But I'm more reliable now.

337
00:16:35,694 --> 00:16:37,296
Then there was the
  courier service.

338
00:16:37,296 --> 00:16:39,865
I drove around a lot
 delivering stuff.

339
00:16:39,865 --> 00:16:41,166
Packages and stuff.

340
00:16:41,166 --> 00:16:42,601
I mean it could
 have been anything.

341
00:16:42,601 --> 00:16:44,636
For all I know I could
 have been delivering drugs.

342
00:16:44,636 --> 00:16:46,138
But I wasn't.

343
00:16:46,138 --> 00:16:46,972
Are you okay?

344
00:16:49,108 --> 00:16:51,243
- I have a little
  bit of headache.

345
00:16:51,243 --> 00:16:53,245
- Oh you should probably
take the day off.

346
00:16:54,413 --> 00:16:56,281
- It's been very nice
 meeting you Francis.

347
00:16:56,281 --> 00:16:58,317
I hope you'll be
very happy here.

348
00:16:58,317 --> 00:16:59,151
- Oh I got the job?

349
00:16:59,151 --> 00:17:00,486
- Yes.

350
00:17:00,486 --> 00:17:01,987
- Don't you want
  me to take a test?

351
00:17:01,987 --> 00:17:03,288
- Well Natalie will
 be here shortly.

352
00:17:03,288 --> 00:17:04,556
She'll show you around.

353
00:17:04,556 --> 00:17:05,691
- I'll be very happy
 to take a drug test.

354
00:17:05,691 --> 00:17:06,892
- That's not necessary Francis.

355
00:17:06,892 --> 00:17:08,394
- A lie detector test?

356
00:17:08,394 --> 00:17:10,162
- No, if you just take a
  seat in the outer office--

357
00:17:10,162 --> 00:17:11,263
- You know what,
 I've always wanted to

358
00:17:11,263 --> 00:17:12,531
take a lie detector test.

359
00:17:12,531 --> 00:17:14,266
I actually thought
  that would be fun.

360
00:17:14,266 --> 00:17:15,801
I wanna thank you so so much.

361
00:17:15,801 --> 00:17:16,702
I won't let you down.

362
00:17:16,702 --> 00:17:18,170
I'll do a fantastic job.

363
00:17:18,170 --> 00:17:19,772
You won't be sorry.

364
00:17:22,741 --> 00:17:23,942
- I've hired a maniac.

365
00:17:27,813 --> 00:17:30,582
(faint clanking)

366
00:17:44,663 --> 00:17:46,231
- Do you see those women?

367
00:17:46,231 --> 00:17:48,100
They're sewing
 labels into garments.

368
00:17:48,100 --> 00:17:50,035
They get credit for
 the number they do.

369
00:18:05,150 --> 00:18:07,653
You can pack or sew labels.

370
00:18:07,653 --> 00:18:09,421
- It's easy, who makes the most?

371
00:18:09,421 --> 00:18:10,989
- Depends on how fast you go.

372
00:18:10,989 --> 00:18:12,991
It's pay by the piece.

373
00:18:12,991 --> 00:18:14,960
- I'll pack, I'll
  be a great packer.

374
00:18:16,061 --> 00:18:17,996
- [Nat] You can start
 now if you want.

375
00:18:17,996 --> 00:18:19,465
- Well that sounds thrilling.

376
00:18:20,666 --> 00:18:22,401
- Why don't you take
 the middle position.

377
00:18:22,401 --> 00:18:23,235
- Terrific.

378
00:18:35,681 --> 00:18:38,016
- You're not gonna start
in are you Frannie?

379
00:18:38,016 --> 00:18:40,085
- I'm not doing anything.

380
00:18:45,824 --> 00:18:47,826
- [Narrator] Here ya go.

381
00:18:56,268 --> 00:18:58,237
- They're big.

382
00:18:58,237 --> 00:18:59,972
- I did this as a favor to you.

383
00:19:01,073 --> 00:19:02,641
- I appreciate that Mr. Osteen.

384
00:19:04,543 --> 00:19:06,612
- You found her
 something downstairs?

385
00:19:06,612 --> 00:19:08,447
- I did sir.

386
00:19:08,447 --> 00:19:10,549
- She's not really
suited for office work.

387
00:19:11,416 --> 00:19:12,584
- I know.

388
00:19:12,584 --> 00:19:13,785
- Well she's probably
 not even suited

389
00:19:13,785 --> 00:19:15,387
for factory work either.

390
00:19:15,387 --> 00:19:16,221
- No sir.

391
00:19:17,189 --> 00:19:19,258
- Just keep an eye.

392
00:19:20,158 --> 00:19:20,993
- I will sir.

393
00:19:23,095 --> 00:19:25,998
- How long do you think
 she'll be staying on with us?

394
00:19:25,998 --> 00:19:27,199
- Not long.

395
00:19:27,199 --> 00:19:29,568
Frannie doesn't
 stick to things much.

396
00:19:29,568 --> 00:19:31,003
- Good.

397
00:19:31,003 --> 00:19:31,837
Good.

398
00:19:33,005 --> 00:19:34,806
You got a couple of
 aspirin out there?

399
00:19:35,908 --> 00:19:37,342
- I'll see what I can do sir.

400
00:19:44,950 --> 00:19:46,552
- How's the kid?

401
00:19:46,552 --> 00:19:47,786
- Don't ask.

402
00:19:47,786 --> 00:19:48,921
He was up all night.

403
00:19:48,921 --> 00:19:50,355
Heat rash.

404
00:19:50,355 --> 00:19:52,291
- Baking soda, will
 clear him right up.

405
00:19:53,926 --> 00:19:55,627
- Whew, it's like
  an oven in here.

406
00:19:58,197 --> 00:20:00,465
- I always heard she was
 hot stuff, didn't you Grace?

407
00:20:00,465 --> 00:20:02,734
(laughing)

408
00:20:05,537 --> 00:20:08,340
- It's probably better I don't
 hit someone my first day.

409
00:20:12,978 --> 00:20:15,147
- Frannie, why
 you've been hiding?

410
00:20:15,147 --> 00:20:17,449
- 'Cause I didn't wanna
see people like you.

411
00:20:17,449 --> 00:20:18,650
(chuckling)

412
00:20:18,650 --> 00:20:20,285
- Frannie back in town.

413
00:20:21,253 --> 00:20:22,087
Owe!

414
00:20:23,422 --> 00:20:25,624
- Looks like the boys
 are glad she's back.

415
00:20:25,624 --> 00:20:28,126
(perky music)

416
00:20:32,030 --> 00:20:33,398
- Stupid idiot machine!

417
00:20:33,398 --> 00:20:35,667
(clanking)

418
00:20:40,038 --> 00:20:41,573
I can do it.

419
00:20:41,573 --> 00:20:42,874
Yes I can do it.

420
00:20:43,742 --> 00:20:44,710
I can do it.

421
00:21:04,563 --> 00:21:07,633
What's a good count
 for an average day?

422
00:21:07,633 --> 00:21:08,967
- About 1,000.

423
00:21:08,967 --> 00:21:10,235
- 1,000?

424
00:21:10,235 --> 00:21:12,237
How much do you make for that?

425
00:21:12,237 --> 00:21:13,538
- $60.

426
00:21:13,538 --> 00:21:14,940
- $60, oh my god.

427
00:21:21,346 --> 00:21:23,949
- No snacks, except at break,

428
00:21:23,949 --> 00:21:25,751
and no eating on the line!

429
00:21:25,751 --> 00:21:26,585
- Sorry.

430
00:21:28,353 --> 00:21:29,621
Why didn't y'all tell me?

431
00:21:31,256 --> 00:21:32,124
- You didn't ask.

432
00:21:33,692 --> 00:21:34,526
- Thanks.

433
00:21:36,795 --> 00:21:38,463
I got mixed up on my cardboard.

434
00:21:41,266 --> 00:21:42,634
- [Narrator] One up!

435
00:21:42,634 --> 00:21:43,435
Yes.

436
00:21:47,939 --> 00:21:48,907
- Skirt tight enough?

437
00:21:48,907 --> 00:21:50,075
- I had that on earlier.

438
00:21:51,076 --> 00:21:52,277
- Baby!

439
00:21:52,277 --> 00:21:53,245
- Hey, you sit
 right here Frannie!

440
00:21:53,245 --> 00:21:54,413
- Drop dead.

441
00:21:54,413 --> 00:21:56,381
(laughing)

442
00:21:56,381 --> 00:21:59,017
(train honking)

443
00:22:20,639 --> 00:22:22,107
Oh, I didn't see you.

444
00:22:22,974 --> 00:22:24,576
- [Male] I know.

445
00:22:24,576 --> 00:22:26,344
- Is it okay to be here?

446
00:22:26,344 --> 00:22:27,179
- [Male] Yup.

447
00:22:28,280 --> 00:22:29,548
- I don't know the rules.

448
00:22:33,485 --> 00:22:34,720
- This is fine.

449
00:22:37,222 --> 00:22:38,490
- [Frannie] How long
 have you been here?

450
00:22:38,490 --> 00:22:40,525
- Oh not too long.

451
00:22:40,525 --> 00:22:41,993
10 minutes.

452
00:22:41,993 --> 00:22:44,463
Don't mind me, go ahead,
take a nap if you want.

453
00:22:44,463 --> 00:22:45,297
- Thanks.

454
00:22:48,467 --> 00:22:49,968
What do you do here?

455
00:22:51,737 --> 00:22:53,004
- I'm the foreman.

456
00:22:53,004 --> 00:22:53,839
- The foreman?

457
00:22:55,073 --> 00:22:58,143
Oh, is it okay for
  you to talk to me?

458
00:22:58,143 --> 00:22:58,944
I just pack.

459
00:22:59,878 --> 00:23:00,612
I'm a packer.

460
00:23:04,816 --> 00:23:05,650
- I'm Ruben.

461
00:23:06,752 --> 00:23:07,986
- I'm Frannie.

462
00:23:07,986 --> 00:23:08,820
- I know.

463
00:23:09,855 --> 00:23:11,089
- Oh.

464
00:23:11,089 --> 00:23:12,691
Yeah, everybody's
  heard about me.

465
00:23:17,662 --> 00:23:19,931
- Well, the first day's
always the toughest.

466
00:23:21,032 --> 00:23:23,602
Most of 'em quit
 after the first week.

467
00:23:23,602 --> 00:23:24,836
If you can get past that,

468
00:23:27,139 --> 00:23:27,973
it gets easier.

469
00:23:31,243 --> 00:23:32,778
Hang in there Frannie.

470
00:23:34,312 --> 00:23:35,147
- Thanks.

471
00:23:45,924 --> 00:23:47,259
- [Nat] Congratulations.

472
00:23:47,259 --> 00:23:49,027
- [Frannie] On what?

473
00:23:49,027 --> 00:23:50,996
- Lasting a day.

474
00:23:50,996 --> 00:23:53,198
- I ache all over.

475
00:23:53,198 --> 00:23:54,766
I made $15.

476
00:23:56,401 --> 00:23:57,769
I wish mama was here.

477
00:23:59,237 --> 00:24:02,207
She'd say, "I'm so proud of
 you Frannie, you didn't quit."

478
00:24:04,442 --> 00:24:05,911
You think she can see us Nat?

479
00:24:07,946 --> 00:24:09,614
Maybe she was looking
 down at the factory

480
00:24:09,614 --> 00:24:11,082
and she saw me working.

481
00:24:12,517 --> 00:24:14,286
- I was proud of you Frannie.

482
00:24:16,221 --> 00:24:17,856
- I bought us
 chicken for supper.

483
00:24:19,124 --> 00:24:20,292
- Thanks.

484
00:24:20,292 --> 00:24:22,027
- You remember
 daddy loved chicken?

485
00:24:25,764 --> 00:24:27,499
You ever wonder where he is?

486
00:24:28,633 --> 00:24:29,467
- Not really.

487
00:24:32,137 --> 00:24:33,572
- I ate most of it.

488
00:24:33,572 --> 00:24:35,874
There's two wings
  and a thigh left,

489
00:24:35,874 --> 00:24:37,242
but I couldn't stop myself.

490
00:24:38,443 --> 00:24:40,078
- It's okay.

491
00:24:40,078 --> 00:24:40,912
- Who's Ruben?

492
00:24:42,180 --> 00:24:43,682
- Ruben Mason?

493
00:24:43,682 --> 00:24:44,583
- I don't know.

494
00:24:44,583 --> 00:24:46,485
- The one at the mill?

495
00:24:46,485 --> 00:24:47,986
- Yeah, who is he?

496
00:24:49,054 --> 00:24:51,056
- He's nice, solid.

497
00:24:52,357 --> 00:24:53,458
- Too bad.

498
00:24:53,458 --> 00:24:55,727
- Dependable like Jake.

499
00:24:55,727 --> 00:24:57,229
- How sad.

500
00:24:58,363 --> 00:24:59,764
- Did he ask you out?

501
00:24:59,764 --> 00:25:01,199
- No, he's spying on me.

502
00:25:03,568 --> 00:25:05,170
- If he asks you out say yes.

503
00:25:06,071 --> 00:25:07,205
- Another Jake.

504
00:25:07,205 --> 00:25:08,039
(laughing)

505
00:25:08,039 --> 00:25:09,074
No thanks.

506
00:25:21,620 --> 00:25:23,388
Today I'm gonna
 make more than $15.

507
00:25:25,423 --> 00:25:27,726
- Jake and I spoke to the
  realtor about the house.

508
00:25:27,726 --> 00:25:29,527
- I don't wanna hear it.

509
00:25:29,527 --> 00:25:32,130
(upbeat music)

510
00:25:47,646 --> 00:25:50,348
- Is he ever gonna fix
 this blasted thing?

511
00:25:50,348 --> 00:25:51,182
- Dream on baby.

512
00:25:54,085 --> 00:25:55,654
- How long til break?

513
00:25:55,654 --> 00:25:56,454
- 15 minutes.

514
00:25:57,489 --> 00:25:58,323
- I'm dying.

515
00:25:59,391 --> 00:26:00,225
Ethel!

516
00:26:01,359 --> 00:26:02,694
Where is she?

517
00:26:02,694 --> 00:26:05,063
- Ethel's probably in
 the bathroom herself.

518
00:26:05,063 --> 00:26:05,997
- I gotta go.

519
00:26:05,997 --> 00:26:06,965
- They'll dock you.

520
00:26:06,965 --> 00:26:07,866
- Stupid rule.

521
00:26:19,244 --> 00:26:20,312
Oh god!

522
00:26:20,312 --> 00:26:21,713
My ring is caught!

523
00:26:21,713 --> 00:26:23,048
- Get someone to turn it off!

524
00:26:23,048 --> 00:26:23,982
Go get someone!

525
00:26:23,982 --> 00:26:25,250
Go!

526
00:26:25,250 --> 00:26:30,255
- [Grace] Help, we
 need some help here!

527
00:26:33,191 --> 00:26:34,025
- Don't you walk away from me!

528
00:26:34,025 --> 00:26:34,859
- Report me!

529
00:26:34,859 --> 00:26:35,794
- I will!

530
00:26:35,794 --> 00:26:36,995
- The machines are antiquated!

531
00:26:36,995 --> 00:26:38,196
- There's nothing wrong
with our equipment!

532
00:26:38,196 --> 00:26:39,698
- Nothing wrong
 with the equipment!

533
00:26:39,698 --> 00:26:41,499
Bernie's got six, seven, and
 nine are all making metal!

534
00:26:41,499 --> 00:26:42,734
They're worn out!

535
00:26:42,734 --> 00:26:44,102
- Well we can't
  afford to fix 'em!

536
00:26:45,437 --> 00:26:47,038
- Oh well that's it then.

537
00:26:47,038 --> 00:26:48,773
That's the bottom line,
it's about the money.

538
00:26:48,773 --> 00:26:50,675
- If the workers just used
  the machine properly--

539
00:26:50,675 --> 00:26:51,843
- It's not about workers,
  it's about greed!

540
00:26:51,843 --> 00:26:53,311
It's cheaper to patch
 up the employees

541
